 vice presidential election box|ev=352|to_win=177}}\n'''Source:''' {{National Archives EV source| year=1872| as of=July 31, 2005}}\n\n==== Breakdown by ticket ====\n{{start U.S. electoral vote box| ev_footnote=<sup>(a)</sup>}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Ulysses S. Grant| vp_name=Henry Wilson| ev=286}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Thomas Andrews Hendricks| vp_name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| ev=41 .. 42}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=Alfred Holt Colquitt| ev=5}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=George Washington Julian| ev=4 .. 5}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=Thomas E. Bramlette| ev=3}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Horace Greeley| vp_name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| ev=3 <sup>(b)</sup>}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=John McAuley Palmer| ev=2 .. 3}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Charles J. Jenkins| vp_name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| ev=2}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=Nathaniel Prentiss Banks| ev=1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=Willis Benson Machen| ev=1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| vp_name=William Slocum Groesbeck| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=David Davis| vp_name=Benjamin Gratz Brown| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=David Davis| vp_name=William Slocum Groesbeck| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=David Davis| vp_name=George Washington Julian| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=David Davis| vp_name=John McAuley Palmer| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Thomas Andrews Hendricks| vp_name=William Slocum Groesbeck| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Thomas Andrews Hendricks| vp_name=George Washington Julian| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{U.S. electoral vote box row| name=Thomas Andrews Hendricks| vp_name=John McAuley Palmer| ev=0 .. 1}}\n{{end U.S. electoral vote box}}\n<sup>(a)</sup> ''The used sources had insufficient data to determine the pairings of 4 electoral votes in Missouri; therefore, the possible tickets are listed with the minimum and maximum possible number of electoral votes each.''<br />\n<sup>(b)</sup> ''Brown's vice-presidential votes were counted, but the presidential votes for Horace Greeley were rejected since he was ineligible for the office of President due to his death.''\n\n==Demise of the Liberal Republicans==\n\nThough the national party organization disappeared after 1872, several Liberal Republican members continued to serve in Congress after the 1872 elections. Most Liberal Republican Congressmen eventually joined the Democratic Party. Outside of the South, some Liberal Republicans sought the creation of a new party opposed to Republicans, but Democrats were unwilling to abandon their old party affiliation and even relatively successful efforts like Wisconsin's [[Reform Party (19th-century Wisconsin)|Reform Party]] collapsed. Even the strong Missouri Liberal Republican Party collapsed as the Democrats re-established themselves as the major opposition party to the Republicans. In the following years, former Liberal Republicans became members in good standing of both major parties.<ref>Ross, pp. 192-239</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]]\n* [[American election campaigns in the 19th century]]\n* [[History of the United States (1865\u20131918)]]\n* [[Third Party System]]\n* [[Reconstruction era]]\n* [[Second inauguration of Ulysses S. Grant]]\n* [[1872 United States House of Representatives elections]]\n* [[1872 and 1873 United States Senate elections]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''American  Annual Cyclopedia...for 1872'' (1873), comprehensive collection of facts [https://books.google.com/books?id=Jp8YAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&